segments.text: campus.
Was Pinky Downs there yet?
Pinky was in Temple, Texas at that time, but he had a daughter named Gray, Gray Downs, and she was a good looking thing.
And Bobby Early, who was my partner in the tennis courts, used to go with Gray.
He used to go to Temple.
And Pinky at that time was still a big Aggie supporter, but he was in Temple then.
Now, was Lupo, did he have a place?
Yeah, Lupo had his bookshop up at the North Gate.
And he had some nickname.
Old Army?
Old Army Lou?
Yeah, Old Army Lou.
And he was a good friend of Tiger Teague's, I remember.
But this is before they both became famous.
Yeah, right.
But he had a bookstore, I'd say.
Who were, did any famous people come to visit while you were?
Yes.
Roosevelt did.
Describe that, please.
You can see a picture of it.
Yes, sir.
I just did.
Right.
Roosevelt, Eliot Roosevelt was on the Board of Regents, President Roosevelt's son.
President Roosevelt's son, Eliot, was on the Board, and he was the one that got Roosevelt there.
And the governor of Texas then was Jimmy Allred.
And so they came in this open touring car, and he reviewed the Corps, Roosevelt did.
And I think they had a stand where he could hold onto the stand while he reviewed the Corps.
Were you and your buddies aware
of how crippled he was.
Oh, yes.
Oh, yeah.
You were here?
Oh, yeah, we did.
Ed Lee, who was in that picture, Ed was a handsome guy.
He was the captain of the basketball team, one of my best friends.
But he was the corps commander when Roosevelt was there.
And he's in the picture with Roosevelt.
But we were all
awed by the fact that the President of the United States would come down to review the Corps.
Did he make a speech?
He must have, but I don't recall it.
I just recall it in passing in review because I was captain of E Battery and presenting arms before Roosevelt.
I remember that.
I wanted to be sure that I didn't stick my saber in the ground, you know.
Was he on the campus very long?
I don't think he was there very long.
I think it was certainly a one-day visit.
Did many people from off campus come to see him?
Yes, a lot of people came for the review, for this review.
Did any other famous people come to visit?
Let me see who else they had.
They had some famous bands that came to play for the Chordances.
Such as?
I think Tommy Dorsey, among others.
And let me see.
Tommy Dorsey and there was a
I can't think of it right now.
You go to summer camp which year?
It was in my junior year.
After your junior year?
Yeah, right after your junior year, between your junior year and senior year.
Where did you go?
Went to Camp Bullis and we fired, to save money at that time, the field artillery had French 75s.
And to save money, the Army had 37 millimeters on top of the 75, so that the shells were actually 37 millimeters.
But you had the same thing, the firing and then correcting fire and so forth.
And that summer camp duty lasted how long?
I think it was either six or eight weeks, but right outside of San Antonio.
How did that compare to Corps life?
Well, I think core life prepared you for this.
You lived in tents, and you had, I think, four guys to a tent, but there was no difference in chain of command or anything.
And most people really enjoyed summer camp.
Was it hot?
Oh, yes.
San Antonio at this time of the year, you know, it was...
After the summer camp, that's when the attack officers evaluated people and that's when they decided who would be captain or whatever.
So you didn't know when you went to summer camp that you were going to be company commander?
Oh no, no, no.
That wasn't decided until after that.
Did you guys, did you Aggies feel at summer camp that you were better prepared
than the ROTC boys from other places?
Well, let's see.
At our camp, I think we were the only ones there.
I think we were just A&M people there.
So who went to camp from A&M that year?
Actually, all the juniors.
All the juniors.
Just the juniors.
The juniors went.
300 maybe?
At least, I wouldn't say it was that many because our senior class had a total of 400 and there were others that went to other places.
Now when you were at A&M,
Everybody was in the Corps all four years?
Oh yeah, everybody was in the Corps.
All four years?
All four years, right.
But was everybody getting a commission?
No, no.
And actually there were some guys that were called day dodgers who lived in Bryan.
They weren't in the Corps.
But everybody was eligible for a commission who graduated.
And so when I graduated, I was commissioned a second lieutenant in the Field Artillery Reserve.
As far as you and your buddies felt,
which of the branches of the Army were the most prestigious?
What was the best to be in?
Well, I really don't think at A&M anybody looked at the best there.
They looked at what people were interested in, like the cavalry.
They had the horse-drawn cavalry then, and people that liked to
ride in the cavalry or in the field artillery because the field artillery was horse-drawn.
And that was one of the reasons I liked the field artillery in addition to the fact that my uncle had been, was a captain, at that time was a captain in the field artillery.
So did you ride a good bit?
Oh, yeah.
Where were the horses kept?
They had stables.
Where?
A lot of horses.
They were over on the other side of the railroad tracks, and you could check the horses out on the weekends, and we used to ride on the weekends.
Where did you ride?
Well, there were big planes out there that you could ride and really race and cavalry charge and all that sort of thing.
Was it on college property?
Oh, yeah, it was on college property.
It was on the other side of the railroad track, on the west side.
But that was a lot of fun.
You had asked me to think about things that really had prepared me in later life, and one of them was horseback riding.
And this has what happened in 1955.
I was part of a group that went to Yemen and negotiated a deal with the old king of Yemen.
And Life magazine wrote a story about it, which I've told you here.
But the pertinent part is that
as we flew to Cairo and then to Djibouti.
And the King sent his airplane over to Dakota or DC-3 and picked us up.
And we flew into Taiz, which was his summer palace.
And there were no hotels there at all.
And we stayed at the guest house.
But when we called on the king, I told him through the interpreter that I admired the stallions that I had seen coming up to Taiz.
And he asked me through the interpreter, did I like to ride?
And I said, yes, I did.
And so the next morning, he sent the fieriest stallion he had down there for me to ride, a horse called Rod.
Fortunately, the horse had a snaffle bit and a curb bit.
After fighting the horse for some time, I was finally able to get on him and ride him off.
He was up on the balcony watching, and the king sent his horse down every morning for me to ride.
So we were there six weeks.
We finally got the concession.
And so after the concession, our interpreter said, do you know why people got this concession?
I said, no.
He said, because you could ride that horse.
And he figured that if, according to the interpreter, that if I had not lied about being able to ride,
that we possibly would observe the things.
So here, there was this deal in Yemen.
Oh, thank you, thank you, thank you.
But here's this Life magazine story in December of 55.
Ah, splendid.
Splendid.
But it's directly related to how did A&M help you in some fashion?
The fact that I could ride that horse was
But you were a horseman before you got to A&M.
You could ride.
Yeah, I could ride before then.
I could ride before then.
But actually, I took in a field artillery at that time.
You had to jump and so forth, and they taught you.
They taught you jumping and so forth.
Although I could ride, I really learned the finer points of riding at A&M.
Back in the spring of your junior year, you must have bought some senior boots.
Right.
Where did you get them?
I got them at Lucchesi's, I think.
Do you remember what they cost?
I think it was $75.
I'm not sure.
And what did you feel like when you put them on to wear for the first time officially at Final Review that spring when you were getting ready to be a senior?
Oh, I thought, you know, this is all that problem of being a fish and so forth has been worth it.
And you bought your senior ring.
Right.
Do you remember what it cost?
I don't recall.
I remember I got it from Fort Worth.
I believe Balfour.
I'm not sure.
I think that was the name of it.
Do you have any good ring stories?
Yes.
I've got one.
I lost my ring and I was on a Southwest Airlines flight to, let me get you the story.
Don't forget you're plugged in.
Oh, I better take this off.
So you lost your ring.
Was it on the Southwest Airlines?
Right, it was on the Southwest Airlines.
Was it ever found?
No, and actually I wrote to Herb Kelleher, head of Southwest, and believe it or not he wrote this letter back.
How splendid, how splendid.
They never found it.
Did you buy another one?
No, I haven't.
So that was your only... That was my... All right, do you have any other ring stories of where you were somewhere on the other side of the world or something?
Yeah, that's in this write-up.
I say it in this that...
They knew it was an Aggie ring?
Oh, yeah, yeah.
They...
Actually, I was in Algeria on a consulting job when the war in Algeria was going on, and I was staying at a hotel there in Algiers.
and everybody had evacuated.
There were lots of bombing and so forth going on during that revolution.
And there were just a few people in the hotel, and I was at the bar one night,
and was sitting there and ordered a drink.
And this guy saw my ring and he said, what class were you in?
And I told him.
And we introduced ourselves.
I forget what class he was in, but we were the only about four people in our hotel.
But he saw the ring.
When you and your classmates were getting ready to graduate from Texas A&M,
What kind of world did you think you were going to be going into and how well prepared did you and your friends think you were?
I thought we were well prepared.
It was actually the beginning of a second depression, 37 and 38.
So jobs were very scarce at that time.
And so we knew that we would...
I'd say most of us thought that we were
well prepared to be in a competitive world.
And I thought I'd be better prepared if I got another degree from MIT, which turned out to be true.
But the A&M experience, I think, prepared you for a competitive world.
Now you graduated in the spring of 37, so there was no war yet.
No.
And the tough thing was simply economics, jobs and paying the bills and so forth.
How did you get admitted to MIT?
Did you think that up or did someone recommend
No, I applied.
But did an A&M faculty member suggest you?
No, this was my idea all the time.
As I say, I had wanted to get a graduate degree from MIT all the time.
So I applied and was accepted.
And I remember there were several other A&M graduates in my class.
One of them was Dr. Silvey, was the head of the Electroengineering Department.
And his son, his name was Silvey, he applied, and he was accepted.
But I think all of us that applied, I think there were about five or six that applied for MIT, and we were all accepted, which showed that
that they regarded the academic background.
When you got there, did you all do well academically up there?
We all did well.
We all graduated, got our degrees.
Describe the formalities of your senior spring.
Commencement, the final review, and so forth.
Right.
Well, we had a ring dance.
At Sebesa?
At Sebesa Hall, right.
We had a ring dance, and I think I had Lillian Street down as my guest, and then we had final review.
Do you remember who the reviewing officer was?
I don't remember who he was.
It was on the drill field.
Right, it was on the drill field.
It's the same as it is now.
Did any family or close friends come?
My sister came.
She came, and she was actually the date of a good friend of mine.
And she came.
My mother didn't come.
What about commencement?
Where was it held?
That was held in...
Gann Hall, which was an impressive, impressive thing.
At that point, how well prepared did you feel A&M had made you?
I thought at commencement, I thought I was where I wanted to be at that time, competitively and so forth.
What creates this Aggie spirit, Aggie pride?
What builds that?
I've given some thought to that and I think what it did in my era was the fact that as fish you went through a very tough
year in which you shared a lot of experiences, some of which were painful and some, though, which you had a lot of fun doing.
And that, I think that, plus the fact that you were
they emphasized, I'd say, duty on a country, which you never forgot.
And that bonding is somewhat different than other schools.
Are there some key
the events of being in the Corps and so forth.
But are there some other events that contribute to that bonding?
Well, I would say your
relationships with whatever team you were on.
A sort of special people you can't forget.
I'll never forget the guys I was on the basketball team with.
And I might just tell you a connection to that story.
When we went over to play Centenary one time in basketball,
We went in the coach's cars.
We were unloading our baggage at the Washington Urey Hotel, and one of the bellboys, a black bellboy, was helping us unload.
And he looked at me and he said, what is you?
Is you the mascot?
I told him, no, I actually played on the team.
Did you all have, in your day, did you all go to muster?
Oh, yes.
Oh, yes.
Where was it held?
Let's see.
Muster was, I think it was held at the administration building, in front of the administration building.
The, you're saying the?
The old administration building.
The old, okay.
I think it was held there, but I'm really not sure.
But at that point,
I read out the names of the guys who had died that year.
And by the time you were a senior, was Silver Tap still staying in your room?
Oh, yeah.
It was still the same.
It was still the same.
At commencement, was every name called and every hand shaken?
Oh, yes.
Yes, at commencement, every name was called.
You went up on the stage and Dr. Walton
gave you a diploma, and shook your hand.
And are those shared experiences key to Aggie spirit?
I think it's part of it, yeah.
Of course, other colleges and so forth have similar type things, except that I think the difference is the hardship part that you go through at the very beginning.
All right, now we've got about a half dozen questions, and these are all the serious ones.
Looking back, what did you learn at A&M that has been important in your life?
Summarize what being an Aggie, why it's important.
The important things, I think, of being an Aggie was
is one that you had an excellent education, excellent basic education.
Two, that you went through a training period in which certain moral values were emphasized, such as duty, honor, country, and truth.
so that in the real world, people who know about Aggies, people who are Aggies, know that when they hire a guy,
he will have certain qualities.
One, that he's got a good basic education.
Two, that he's able to get along with other men.
And three, that character has been emphasized in his training.
I found this to be true in my relations with Aggie employers, but also with the executives of other companies.
If you were a consultant to Texas A&M's leaders today,
What advice would you give them regarding A&M's future?
Well, I was a member of the Century Council and was a member of the Target 2000 project in which I was exposed to the answer to your question.
And I think that both of those reports really were pretty comprehensive as to A&M, what they should follow.
And I think Dr. Bowen has carried that out pretty well.
And of course,
Earl Rudder was probably the greatest president A&M ever had, and he carried forward the things that had been recommended.
For example, though, how large should A&M's enrollment become?
As of right now, I think the enrollment should be static, 40,000 plus or whatever, because I think if you try to increase it more, you diminish the quality of teaching there.
And how should the students be selected?
I think the students should be elected on a competitive basis, and there should be certain minimum qualities.
Whereas I understand the problem
of the minorities and certainly want to emphasize diversity, but I think that the standards for them should be the same as anybody else.
So there's a difference of opinion on that, but that's the way I feel.
I've been on the Easterwood Scholarship Board, and we've had discussions about that.
We've had some candidates come up who were submitted to get scholarships.

And somebody, let's say, that had some minority applicant who had an SAT of 1050, even though he might have been in the top 10% of his class, and maybe in a school that is somewhat inferior as to its academic status, it hasn't been
really fair to have that particular person, to me it seems, to go up against somebody who has a 1250.
But what I would think is to make some arrangement where the person goes to a junior college under some sort of a
Otherwise, he's going to be, he'll flunk out and be discouraged and probably end up on drugs.
But I think the junior college thing is the way to go, probably.

what parts or what programs, what activities are dearest to your heart, and I'll phrase that in a different way, if you were going to make a truly substantial gift to Texas A&M, what would you want that gift to be used to do?
I think that particular gift would be the Petroleum Engineering School there is, and of course the U.S. News is rated number one in the country, number two is Texas, number three is Stanford.
But I'd say the gift would be to the Petroleum Engineering School to maintain its standard.
Okay, fun.
What is your favorite Aggie Good Bull story?
There's gotta be some
